+### 7.3a Coexistence with the Compose deployment
+
+13a is explicitly parallel to the existing Compose deployment
+(§1.1). Operators may have BOTH running on the same
+machine — e.g., Compose stack on the local Docker daemon for
+development, plus a `helm install` on a kind/k3s cluster on
+the same host for k8s testing. A few coexistence rules:
+
+- **Helm release name + namespace.** Each `helm install`
+  carries an operator-chosen release name (e.g.,
+  `eden-dev`, `eden-prod`) and namespace
+  (`eden-dev`, `eden-prod`). The chart's resource names are
+  prefixed by the release name via `eden.fullname` in
+  `_helpers.tpl`, so two releases in different namespaces
+  do not collide on resource names. Two releases in the
+  SAME namespace WILL collide (Service / StatefulSet name
+  conflicts) — operators MUST use distinct namespaces per
+  release.
+- **Ingress hostname collisions.** If two releases (or one
+  release + the Compose stack) both want to expose the Web
+  UI or Gitea on the same hostname, the Ingress controller
+  serves whichever was created first; the second's
+  hostname-bound rules are silently ignored or rejected
+  depending on the controller. The chart's
+  `ingress.hosts.webUi` and `ingress.hosts.gitea` values
+  default to per-release-name templates
+  (`{{ .Release.Name }}-webui.example.com` etc.) rather
+  than shared defaults; operators who deliberately want a
+  shared hostname override per release.
+- **Port-forward port collisions on the local machine.**
+  When operators run BOTH a Compose stack and a Helm
+  release on the same machine and use `kubectl port-forward`
+  to access the Helm release's services, they MUST pick
+  ports that don't conflict with Compose's published ports
+  (the Compose stack's `WEB_UI_HOST_PORT` defaults to 8090,
+  Gitea to 3001). The chart's README example uses
+  port-forward targets at 18090 / 13001 (offset by 10000)
+  to avoid collision.
+- **Pre-existing namespace.** `helm install --create-namespace`
+  is safe against an existing namespace; it succeeds and
+  proceeds. Operators with existing resources in the target
+  namespace risk name collisions (per the first bullet);
+  the README recommends a fresh namespace per release.
 
+These rules are deployment-pragmatic, not protocol-level;
+they live in the chart's README rather than chapter 13 of
+the spec.
+
